Purpose

The Memory Engine is responsible for preserving, organising and retrieving company-specific knowledge.

Unlike traditional software, Numera does not process each document independently.

Every interaction contributes to a growing understanding of the company.

Memory is one of Numera’s core strategic assets.

⸻

Philosophy

Knowledge answers:

“What is generally true?”

Memory answers:

“What has happened inside this company?”

Every company develops habits, preferences, exceptions and operational knowledge.

The purpose of the Memory Engine is to preserve that knowledge.

⸻

Objectives

The Memory Engine must:

* remember relevant business information;
* improve future decisions;
* reduce repetitive work;
* preserve historical context;
* remain fully auditable;
* remain editable by authorised users.

⸻

Memory Lifecycle

Every memory follows the same lifecycle.

Observation
↓
Candidate Memory
↓
Validation
↓
Active Memory
↓
Reinforcement
↓
Decay
↓
Archive
↓
Deletion (optional)

Nothing becomes permanent immediately.

⸻

Memory Categories

Supplier Memory

Examples:

Supplier invoices monthly.

Supplier usually applies 21% VAT.

Supplier invoices are normally booked to account 628000.

Supplier has previously sent duplicate invoices.

⸻

Customer Memory

Examples:

Customer pays late.

Customer always requests PDF invoices.

Customer normally disputes transport costs.

⸻

Accounting Memory

Examples:

Fuel expenses use account 629300.

Travel expenses require cost centre allocation.

Subscriptions are accrued monthly.

⸻

Fiscal Memory

Examples:

Reduced VAT applies.

Intracommunity transaction.

Reverse charge applicable.

⸻

User Memory

Examples:

Finance Manager reviews invoices above €5,000.

Controller prefers manual validation for new suppliers.

⸻

Company Memory

Examples:

Month-end closing starts on day 25.

Payroll is processed on the last working day.

Bank reconciliation occurs every Friday.

⸻

Incident Memory

Examples:

Supplier generated duplicate invoices in 2025.

Bank integration failed during migration.

Tax adjustment required manual correction.

⸻

Instruction Memory

Created explicitly by users.

Examples:

“Always review invoices from Supplier X.”

“Never auto-post invoices above €10,000.”

These memories always have priority.

⸻

Memory Attributes

Every memory contains:

* Memory ID
* Category
* Description
* Company
* Related entities
* Created date
* Created by
* Confidence
* Source
* Status
* Expiration policy
* Last used
* Last updated
* Importance
* Tags

⸻

Confidence

Every memory has its own confidence.

Example:

Supplier → Account 628000

Confidence: 98%

Evidence:

52 accepted invoices

Last confirmation:

2 days ago

Confidence changes over time.

⸻

Reinforcement

Every successful reuse increases confidence.

Repeated confirmation strengthens memory.

Repeated correction weakens memory.

Learning is gradual.

⸻

Memory Decay

Not every memory remains valid forever.

Unused memories lose confidence progressively.

Possible reasons:

* supplier changed behaviour;
* accounting policy changed;
* regulation changed;
* company process changed.

Old memories should not dominate current decisions.

⸻

Memory Sources

Memories may originate from:

* explicit user instruction;
* repeated user approval;
* repeated corrections;
* business rules;
* imported ERP history;
* accounting policies;
* administrator configuration.

The origin is always recorded.

⸻

Memory Retrieval

The Memory Engine retrieves memories according to:

* relevance;
* confidence;
* recency;
* context;
* entity relationships.

Not all memories are equally important.

⸻

Conflict Resolution

Conflicting memories may exist.

Example:

Old rule:

Supplier → Account 628000

New behaviour:

Supplier → Account 629000

Numera must:

* detect conflict;
* lower confidence;
* explain the situation;
* request confirmation if necessary.

Hidden conflicts are unacceptable.

⸻

Explainability

Whenever memory influences a recommendation, Numera must explain it.

Example:

“I proposed account 628000 because:

• 48 previous invoices were booked there.

• No corrections were made during the last 18 months.

• The Finance Manager approved this classification repeatedly.”

⸻

Editing Memory

Authorised users may:

* create memories;
* edit memories;
* deactivate memories;
* archive memories;
* merge duplicate memories;
* restore archived memories.

Nothing should become immutable.

⸻

Security

Memory is company-specific.

No memory should leak between companies.

Access depends on user permissions.

Sensitive memories must be encrypted where appropriate.

⸻

Future Evolution

Future versions may include:

* predictive memories;
* temporal memories;
* seasonal memories;
* collaborative memories;
* workflow memories;
* cross-document reasoning memories.

⸻

Success Criteria

The Memory Engine succeeds when:

* repetitive corrections decrease;
* recommendation quality improves;
* confidence becomes more accurate;
* company knowledge accumulates safely;
* users trust remembered behaviour.

⸻

Closing Statement

The Memory Engine transforms isolated interactions into organisational knowledge.

Every validated experience becomes part of the company’s intelligence.

Memory allows Numera to improve continuously without forcing users to repeat the same decisions.

Knowledge makes Numera intelligent.

Memory makes Numera unique.